Announcement: "Hey seniors! Scared about college apps?…"

Jelani Noble
Created Sep 3Sep 3 (Edited Sep 3) – Deleted
This post is visible to all teachers in this class. It will be permanently deleted in 23 days.
Hey seniors! Scared about college apps? Just avoiding until you absolutely need to do something for your future? There's a free college admissions support program for you hosted by UC Berkeley. It's completely free and all of you are eligible.


 Shout out to Maksim for telling me about this program!

More details here: https://www.campberkeley.org/high-school-student
Intensive track deadline(larger time commitment) is Sep. 3rd at 11:59pm
General track deadline is Sep. 15th at 11:59pm

Announcement: "Hello folks! We have a different bell…"

SARA KETCHAM
Created Aug 30Aug 30 – Deleted
This post is visible to all teachers in this class. It will be permanently deleted in 19 days.
Hello folks! We have a different bell schedule today! Basically, any week we have a holiday, we will just have 4 block days, and get rid of the Monday “all 7 periods” day. And Wednesdays will ALWAYS be even / early release.

So for this week, we have Friday off and the schedule will look like…..
  • Monday: 2, 4, 6, 8
  • Tuesday: 1, 3, 5, 7
  • Wednesday: 2, 4, 6, 8
  • Thursday: 1, 3, 5, 7
  • Friday: NO SCHOOL :)

And next week, we have Monday off and the schedule will look like…..
  • Monday: NO SCHOOL
  • Tuesday: 1, 3, 5, 7
  • Wednesday: 2, 4, 6, 8
  • Thursday: 1, 3, 5, 7
  • Friday: 2, 4, 6, 8
I’ve attached an image with this week’s schedule :)

    5. Assignment
      2.05 CSS & Bootstrap Final Assessment
      Due Today
      Due Today
      Posted Aug 30 (Edited Sep 8)
      AssignedEstigfend
      Same as last time! This is the FINAL CSS and Bootstrap assessment. Your job is to LEARN these both before you do this. If you are not done with the Udemy content, FINISH THAT before you do this assessment.

      Make sure you have tried the Udemy assessments in videos #25 and 31 to test your own learning BEFORE you try this assessment


      What to do:
      • Build a basic webpage with the elements required (attached below -> download the file and save it in your GitHub folder)
      • File Management: The bootstrap assessment file attached to this assignment should become your new index.html BUT DO NOT DELETE your old HTML assessment file.  That will be linked from the bootstrap file.
      • Record a screencast showing the browser AND code where you talk through the code to show you understand the learning targets below.  You MUST go back and forth from the code to the browser. You are making your understanding visible. No need to read through the visible website, we can see that :)
      • The screencast should be ~1-2 minutes
      • Use screencastify (a chrome extension) or any other free screencast ap
      Optional: 
      • In ~30-60 seconds, briefly explain something you geeked out on, or how you got unstuck when you had a problem
      If there is time in class, you are welcome to talk through your website and code with one of the teachers instead of recording a screencast!

      What to turn in:
      • The screencast video
      • Your github link

2.05 CSS & Bootstrap Final Assessment

SARA KETCHAM

Aug 30 (Edited Sep 8)

Due Today
Add class comment
Same as last time! This is the FINAL CSS and Bootstrap assessment. Your job is to LEARN these both before you do this. If you are not done with the Udemy content, FINISH THAT before you do this assessment.

Make sure you have tried the Udemy assessments in videos #25 and 31 to test your own learning BEFORE you try this assessment


What to do:
  • Build a basic webpage with the elements required (attached below -> download the file and save it in your GitHub folder)
  • File Management: The bootstrap assessment file attached to this assignment should become your new index.html BUT DO NOT DELETE your old HTML assessment file.  That will be linked from the bootstrap file.
  • Record a screencast showing the browser AND code where you talk through the code to show you understand the learning targets below.  You MUST go back and forth from the code to the browser. You are making your understanding visible. No need to read through the visible website, we can see that :)
  • The screencast should be ~1-2 minutes
  • Use screencastify (a chrome extension) or any other free screencast ap
Optional: 
  • In ~30-60 seconds, briefly explain something you geeked out on, or how you got unstuck when you had a problem
If there is time in class, you are welcome to talk through your website and code with one of the teachers instead of recording a screencast!

What to turn in:
  • The screencast video
  • Your github link
